<HEADLINE>
<P>
TALKS GO THROUGH HOLIDAY IN JAPANESE EFFORT TO BUY MCA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Representatives of Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. and MCA Inc. reversed an 
earlier plan to take a holiday break, and bargained through Thanksgiving in New 
York without reaching an agreement under which the Japanese company would buy 
MCA. 
</P>
<P>
Individuals close to the bargaining have said that Matsushita has offered in 
the area of $70 a share, but that MCA is holding out for at least $75 a share. 
</P>
<P>
Creative Artists Agency Chairman Michael Ovitz, a top Matsushita 
representative, did not attend Thursday's negotiations. A spokesman said he was 
in Los Angeles with his family and would return to New York when needed. 
</P>
<P>
MCA Chairman Lew R. Wasserman apparently remained in New York through the 
holiday. Further meetings are expected today, and may go through the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen for both sides declined to comment on the talks, but people familiar 
with the discussions said the two sides almost reached an impasse Wednesday 
night before some changes in position allowed the discussions to continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
