<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
DANGER SEEN IN TAN-LINKED ADS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ads with sexy bronzed models should be required to carry health warnings that 
tanning can cause skin cancer, medical specialists said today. 
</P>
<P>
The advertising, fashion and marketing industries are irresponsibly promoting 
tans, counteracting efforts to encourage Australians to reduce their 
skin-cancer risk, the Australasian College of Dermatologists said. 
</P>
<P>
"I believe that each of these pictures should in fact carry a warning, similar 
to those found on cigarette packets: suntanning is a cancer hazard," Dr. Alan 
Cooper, the college's honorary secretary, told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
"When I see parents with very young babies on beaches with no protection, I 
think that is child abuse," he added. 
</P>
<P>
Cooper called for a concerted effort to promote the image that "the pale 
Australian is in, and the bronzed Aussie is out." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112390-0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 312822 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 23, 1990, Friday, P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part P; Page 3; Column 1; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
